{
  "cells": [
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "title: \"Double Integrals over General Regions\"\n",
        "subtitle: \"Type I and Type II regions, reversing order, area, mass, and probability\"\n",
        "format:\n",
        "  html:\n",
        "    toc: true\n",
        "    number-sections: true\n",
        "execute:\n",
        "  echo: true\n",
        "  warning: false\n",
        "  message: false\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "> **Chapter goal.** Rectangles are the training ground for double integrals, but most meaningful regions are not rectangles. This chapter develops double integrals over curved and irregular plane regions. The main skill is translating a geometric region into correct limits of integration, choosing an efficient order, and interpreting the result as area, volume, mass, average value, or probability.\n",
        "\n",
        "A double integral over a general region has the same conceptual meaning as before:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\iint_D f(x,y)\\,dA\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "adds the values of $f$ over a two-dimensional region $D$. The new difficulty is that $D$ may be bounded by curves. Instead of constant limits such as $a\\le x\\le b$ and $c\\le y\\le d$, the inner limits often depend on the outer variable.\n",
        "\n",
        "This chapter is a bridge from rectangular integration to the geometric and computational thinking needed in probability, statistics, machine learning, numerical methods, and vector calculus.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Learning objectives\n",
        "\n",
        "After studying this chapter, you should be able to:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. describe Type I regions using inequalities of the form $a\\le x\\le b$, $p(x)\\le y\\le q(x)$;\n",
        "2. describe Type II regions using inequalities of the form $c\\le y\\le d$, $g(y)\\le x\\le h(y)$;\n",
        "3. set up and evaluate double integrals over nonrectangular regions;\n",
        "4. sketch a region from integral limits and write integral limits from a sketch;\n",
        "5. reverse the order of integration when it simplifies the computation;\n",
        "6. compute area using $\\iint_D 1\\,dA$;\n",
        "7. split a complicated region into simpler pieces;\n",
        "8. interpret double integrals over general regions as volume, mass, average value, and probability.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 14.1 Why rectangles are not enough\n",
        "\n",
        "In the previous chapter, the base region was usually a rectangle\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "R=[a,b]\\times[c,d].\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For such a region, Fubini's theorem gives\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\iint_R f(x,y)\\,dA\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\int_a^b\\int_c^d f(x,y)\\,dy\\,dx\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\int_c^d\\int_a^b f(x,y)\\,dx\\,dy.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "But many natural regions are bounded by curves:\n",
        "\n",
        "- a disk or annulus in geometry;\n",
        "- a triangular feasible set in optimization;\n",
        "- a region under a probability-density curve;\n",
        "- the set of parameters satisfying an inequality;\n",
        "- an irregular geographic region in spatial modeling;\n",
        "- a decision region in classification.\n",
        "\n",
        "For example, the region below the parabola $y=4-x^2$ and above the line $y=3x$ is not a rectangle. Its vertical height changes as $x$ changes. A double integral over this region must reflect that changing geometry."
      ],
      "id": "0964d855"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 6.5
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: fig-ch14-nonrectangular-region\n",
        "#| fig-cap: A nonrectangular region bounded by a parabola and a line. The vertical height of the region changes with x.\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "x = np.linspace(0, 1, 300)\n",
        "y_top = 4 - x**2\n",
        "y_bottom = 3*x\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6.5, 5))\n",
        "ax.plot(x, y_top, label='$y=4-x^2$')\n",
        "ax.plot(x, y_bottom, label='$y=3x$')\n",
        "ax.fill_between(x, y_bottom, y_top, alpha=0.25)\n",
        "for x0 in [0.2, 0.5, 0.8]:\n",
        "    ax.plot([x0, x0], [3*x0, 4-x0**2], linewidth=2)\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('$x$')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('$y$')\n",
        "ax.set_title('Region with variable vertical slices')\n",
        "ax.set_xlim(-0.2, 1.3)\n",
        "ax.set_ylim(-0.2, 4.5)\n",
        "ax.grid(True, alpha=0.25)\n",
        "ax.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "fig-ch14-nonrectangular-region",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "The key skill is to decide how to slice the region.\n",
        "\n",
        "- A **vertical slice** leads to limits $p(x)\\le y\\le q(x)$.\n",
        "- A **horizontal slice** leads to limits $g(y)\\le x\\le h(y)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "The same region may be easy in one direction and difficult in the other.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 14.2 Type I regions: vertical slicing\n",
        "\n",
        "A plane region $D$ is called a **Type I region** if it can be described as\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "D=\n",
        "\\{(x,y):a\\le x\\le b,\\ p(x)\\le y\\le q(x)\\},\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $p$ and $q$ are continuous functions and $p(x)\\le q(x)$ for $a\\le x\\le b$.\n",
        "\n",
        "Geometrically, we move from left to right. For each fixed $x$, the variable $y$ begins at the lower curve $y=p(x)$ and ends at the upper curve $y=q(x)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-important}\n",
        "## Double integral over a Type I region\n",
        "\n",
        "If $D=\\{(x,y):a\\le x\\le b,\\ p(x)\\le y\\le q(x)\\}$ and $f$ is continuous on $D$, then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\iint_D f(x,y)\\,dA\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\int_a^b\\int_{p(x)}^{q(x)} f(x,y)\\,dy\\,dx.\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "The inner integral adds along a vertical slice. The outer integral adds all slices from $x=a$ to $x=b$."
      ],
      "id": "48ed85b9"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 6.5
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: fig-ch14-type-i-template\n",
        "#| fig-cap: A Type I region is described by left-to-right limits and vertical slices.\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "x = np.linspace(0, 3, 400)\n",
        "p = 0.4 + 0.2*np.sin(2*x)\n",
        "q = 2.2 + 0.25*np.cos(1.5*x)\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6.5, 5))\n",
        "ax.plot(x, p, label='$y=p(x)$')\n",
        "ax.plot(x, q, label='$y=q(x)$')\n",
        "ax.fill_between(x, p, q, alpha=0.25)\n",
        "for x0 in np.linspace(0.5, 2.5, 5):\n",
        "    p0 = 0.4 + 0.2*np.sin(2*x0)\n",
        "    q0 = 2.2 + 0.25*np.cos(1.5*x0)\n",
        "    ax.plot([x0, x0], [p0, q0], linewidth=2)\n",
        "ax.text(0, p[0]-0.25, '$a$', ha='center')\n",
        "ax.text(3, p[-1]-0.25, '$b$', ha='center')\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('$x$')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('$y$')\n",
        "ax.set_title('Type I region')\n",
        "ax.grid(True, alpha=0.25)\n",
        "ax.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "fig-ch14-type-i-template",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Example 14.1: A region between a parabola and a line\n",
        "\n",
        "Let $D$ be the region in the first quadrant bounded by\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "y=4-x^2\n",
        "\\qquad \\text{and} \\qquad\n",
        " y=3x.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Compute\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\iint_D 2xy\\,dA.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "**Step 1: Find the intersection points.**\n",
        "\n",
        "Set the curves equal:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "4-x^2=3x.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "x^2+3x-4=0,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "(x+4)(x-1)=0.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The first-quadrant intersection has $x=1$, and then $y=3$. The region begins at $x=0$ and ends at $x=1$.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Step 2: Identify lower and upper curves.**\n",
        "\n",
        "For $0\\le x\\le 1$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "3x\\le y\\le 4-x^2.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Therefore\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "D=\n",
        "\\{(x,y):0\\le x\\le 1,\\ 3x\\le y\\le 4-x^2\\}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "**Step 3: Set up and evaluate.**\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{aligned}\n",
        "\\iint_D 2xy\\,dA\n",
        "&=\n",
        "\\int_0^1\\int_{3x}^{4-x^2} 2xy\\,dy\\,dx \\\\\n",
        "&=\n",
        "\\int_0^1 x\\left[y^2\\right]_{3x}^{4-x^2}\\,dx \\\\\n",
        "&=\n",
        "\\int_0^1 x\\left((4-x^2)^2-9x^2\\right)\\,dx \\\\\n",
        "&=\n",
        "\\int_0^1 \\left(16x-17x^3+x^5\\right)\\,dx \\\\\n",
        "&=\n",
        "\\left[8x^2-\\frac{17}{4}x^4+\\frac{1}{6}x^6\\right]_0^1 \\\\\n",
        "&=\n",
        "8-\\frac{17}{4}+\\frac{1}{6}\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\frac{47}{12}.\n",
        "\\end{aligned}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The result is positive because $2xy\\ge 0$ on the first-quadrant region."
      ],
      "id": "cbf5f22b"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 6.5
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: fig-ch14-parabola-line-region\n",
        "#| fig-cap: The region 0 <= x <= 1, 3x <= y <= 4 - x^2 used in Example 14.1.\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "x = np.linspace(0, 1, 400)\n",
        "y_low = 3*x\n",
        "y_high = 4 - x**2\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6.5, 5))\n",
        "ax.plot(x, y_low, label='$y=3x$')\n",
        "ax.plot(x, y_high, label='$y=4-x^2$')\n",
        "ax.fill_between(x, y_low, y_high, alpha=0.3)\n",
        "ax.scatter([1], [3], zorder=5)\n",
        "ax.text(1.03, 3, '$(1,3)$')\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('$x$')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('$y$')\n",
        "ax.set_title('A Type I region')\n",
        "ax.set_xlim(-0.1, 1.25)\n",
        "ax.set_ylim(-0.2, 4.3)\n",
        "ax.grid(True, alpha=0.25)\n",
        "ax.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "fig-ch14-parabola-line-region",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 14.3 Type II regions: horizontal slicing\n",
        "\n",
        "A plane region $D$ is called a **Type II region** if it can be described as\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "D=\n",
        "\\{(x,y):c\\le y\\le d,\\ g(y)\\le x\\le h(y)\\},\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $g$ and $h$ are continuous functions and $g(y)\\le h(y)$ for $c\\le y\\le d$.\n",
        "\n",
        "Geometrically, we move from bottom to top. For each fixed $y$, the variable $x$ begins at the left curve $x=g(y)$ and ends at the right curve $x=h(y)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-important}\n",
        "## Double integral over a Type II region\n",
        "\n",
        "If $D=\\{(x,y):c\\le y\\le d,\\ g(y)\\le x\\le h(y)\\}$ and $f$ is continuous on $D$, then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\iint_D f(x,y)\\,dA\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\int_c^d\\int_{g(y)}^{h(y)} f(x,y)\\,dx\\,dy.\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::"
      ],
      "id": "f38b3296"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 6.5
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: fig-ch14-type-ii-template\n",
        "#| fig-cap: A Type II region is described by bottom-to-top limits and horizontal slices.\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "y = np.linspace(0, 3, 400)\n",
        "g = 0.4 + 0.2*np.cos(2*y)\n",
        "h = 2.5 + 0.25*np.sin(1.5*y)\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6.5, 5))\n",
        "ax.plot(g, y, label='$x=g(y)$')\n",
        "ax.plot(h, y, label='$x=h(y)$')\n",
        "ax.fill_betweenx(y, g, h, alpha=0.25)\n",
        "for y0 in np.linspace(0.5, 2.5, 5):\n",
        "    g0 = 0.4 + 0.2*np.cos(2*y0)\n",
        "    h0 = 2.5 + 0.25*np.sin(1.5*y0)\n",
        "    ax.plot([g0, h0], [y0, y0], linewidth=2)\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('$x$')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('$y$')\n",
        "ax.set_title('Type II region')\n",
        "ax.grid(True, alpha=0.25)\n",
        "ax.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "fig-ch14-type-ii-template",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Example 14.2: A region between $x=y$ and $x=y^2$\n",
        "\n",
        "Let $D$ be the region bounded by\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "x=y\n",
        "\\qquad \\text{and} \\qquad\n",
        "x=y^2.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Compute\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\iint_D (2xy+6y^2)\\,dA.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "**Step 1: Find the intersections.**\n",
        "\n",
        "Set $y=y^2$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "y^2-y=0,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        " y(y-1)=0.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Thus $y=0$ and $y=1$. For $0\\le y\\le 1$, we have\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "y^2\\le x\\le y.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "**Step 2: Write the Type II integral.**\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\iint_D (2xy+6y^2)\\,dA\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\int_0^1\\int_{y^2}^{y} (2xy+6y^2)\\,dx\\,dy.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "**Step 3: Evaluate.**\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{aligned}\n",
        "\\int_0^1\\int_{y^2}^{y} (2xy+6y^2)\\,dx\\,dy\n",
        "&=\n",
        "\\int_0^1 \\left[x^2y+6xy^2\\right]_{x=y^2}^{x=y}\\,dy \\\\\n",
        "&=\n",
        "\\int_0^1 \\left(y^3+6y^3-y^5-6y^4\\right)\\,dy \\\\\n",
        "&=\n",
        "\\int_0^1 \\left(7y^3-6y^4-y^5\\right)\\,dy \\\\\n",
        "&=\n",
        "\\left[\\frac{7}{4}y^4-\\frac{6}{5}y^5-\\frac{1}{6}y^6\\right]_0^1 \\\\\n",
        "&=\n",
        "\\frac{7}{4}-\\frac{6}{5}-\\frac{1}{6}\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\frac{23}{60}.\n",
        "\\end{aligned}\n",
        "$$"
      ],
      "id": "30ebfe8b"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 6.5
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: fig-ch14-y-vs-y-squared-region\n",
        "#| fig-cap: The region y^2 <= x <= y, 0 <= y <= 1. Horizontal slices make the limits simple.\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "y = np.linspace(0, 1, 400)\n",
        "x_left = y**2\n",
        "x_right = y\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6.5, 5))\n",
        "ax.plot(x_left, y, label='$x=y^2$')\n",
        "ax.plot(x_right, y, label='$x=y$')\n",
        "ax.fill_betweenx(y, x_left, x_right, alpha=0.3)\n",
        "for y0 in [0.2, 0.5, 0.8]:\n",
        "    ax.plot([y0**2, y0], [y0, y0], linewidth=2)\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('$x$')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('$y$')\n",
        "ax.set_title('A Type II region')\n",
        "ax.set_aspect('equal', adjustable='box')\n",
        "ax.grid(True, alpha=0.25)\n",
        "ax.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "fig-ch14-y-vs-y-squared-region",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 14.4 How to choose the order of integration\n",
        "\n",
        "When setting up a double integral, ask two questions.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Question 1. What does a typical slice look like?**\n",
        "\n",
        "A vertical slice is useful if a line $x=\\text{constant}$ enters and exits the region in one piece. A horizontal slice is useful if a line $y=\\text{constant}$ enters and exits the region in one piece.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Question 2. Which order makes the integrand easier?**\n",
        "\n",
        "Sometimes both descriptions are possible, but only one gives an elementary integral.\n",
        "\n",
        "A practical workflow is:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. sketch the curves;\n",
        "2. find intersection points;\n",
        "3. try vertical slices and horizontal slices;\n",
        "4. choose the description with simpler bounds or simpler integration;\n",
        "5. compute only after the geometry is correct.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-tip}\n",
        "## Geometry first, algebra second\n",
        "\n",
        "Many mistakes in double integrals are not integration mistakes. They are region mistakes. Before computing, check:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Does the lower curve really lie below the upper curve?\n",
        "- Does the left curve really lie left of the right curve?\n",
        "- Are the intersection values correct?\n",
        "- Does each slice stay inside the region for the full range of the outer variable?\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 14.5 Reversing the order of integration\n",
        "\n",
        "Some iterated integrals are difficult in the given order but easy after reversing the order.\n",
        "\n",
        "Consider\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\int_0^1\\int_y^1 e^{-x^2}\\,dx\\,dy.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The inner integral\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\int e^{-x^2}\\,dx\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "has no elementary antiderivative. But the integral is not hopeless. The region is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "D=\n",
        "\\{(x,y):0\\le y\\le 1,\\ y\\le x\\le 1\\}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This describes the triangle below the line $y=x$ and inside the unit square. Rewriting in Type I form gives\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "D=\n",
        "\\{(x,y):0\\le x\\le 1,\\ 0\\le y\\le x\\}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Therefore\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\int_0^1\\int_y^1 e^{-x^2}\\,dx\\,dy\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\int_0^1\\int_0^x e^{-x^2}\\,dy\\,dx.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Now $e^{-x^2}$ is constant with respect to $y$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{aligned}\n",
        "\\int_0^1\\int_0^x e^{-x^2}\\,dy\\,dx\n",
        "&=\n",
        "\\int_0^1 xe^{-x^2}\\,dx \\\\\n",
        "&=\n",
        "\\left[-\\frac{1}{2}e^{-x^2}\\right]_0^1 \\\\\n",
        "&=\n",
        "\\frac{1}{2}(1-e^{-1}).\n",
        "\\end{aligned}\n",
        "$$"
      ],
      "id": "51f5ffee"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 6
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: fig-ch14-reversing-order-triangle\n",
        "#| fig-cap: The triangle 0 <= y <= x <= 1. Reversing order turns a difficult integral into an elementary one.\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "x = np.linspace(0, 1, 300)\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 5))\n",
        "ax.plot(x, x, label='$y=x$')\n",
        "ax.plot([0, 1], [0, 0], color='black')\n",
        "ax.plot([1, 1], [0, 1], color='black')\n",
        "ax.fill_between(x, 0, x, alpha=0.3)\n",
        "for x0 in [0.25, 0.5, 0.75]:\n",
        "    ax.plot([x0, x0], [0, x0], linewidth=2)\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('$x$')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('$y$')\n",
        "ax.set_title('Region for reversing order')\n",
        "ax.set_aspect('equal', adjustable='box')\n",
        "ax.grid(True, alpha=0.25)\n",
        "ax.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()"
